"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023211","Home Office","false","2018-12-17","<p>The Home Office ensures asylum seekers are not left destitute by providing appropriate support under section 95 of the Immigration and Asylum Act 1999. The support package usually consists of free, furnished accommodation (with utility bills and council tax paid) and a weekly cash allowance to meet other essential living needs. But those who find accommodation through friends or relatives may be provided with the allowance only. <br> <br>The level of the allowance, currently set at £37.75 per week for each person in the household, is reviewed each year to make sure it is sufficient to cover essential living needs.</p><p>The most recent assessment of the adequacy of the asylum support rates is set out in a report published in March 2018, which can be found at:<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/report-on-review-of-cash-allowance-paid-to-asylum-seekers.%20" target="_blank"> https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/report-on-review-of-cash-allowance-paid-to-asylum-seekers. </a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-12-17T16:57:10.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023211/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023211/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-12-11","Asylum: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what financial support mechanisms his Department has in place to support asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","201228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023212","Home Office","false","2018-12-17","<p>The Home Office publishes data, in its quarterly Immigration Statistics release, on the number of applications for asylum in the UK, broken down by quarter, in table as_01_q (Asylum, volume 1)</p><p>Latest edition available at: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/758192/asylum1-sep-2018-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/758192/asylum1-sep-2018-tables.ods</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-12-17T16:49:15.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023212/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023212/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-12-11","Asylum: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum applications have been received by his Department in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","201229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023213","Home Office","false","2018-12-17","<p>Information on the UK’s resident population is a matter for the Office for National Statistics. The Home Office does not publish estimates on the number of asylum seekers currently living in the UK.</p><p>The Home Office does however publish quarterly breakdowns of the number of asylum applications pending a decision (including dependants), in table as_02_q (asylum, volume 2) of the quarterly Immigration Statistics release. <br>Latest edition available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/758195/asylum2-sep-2018-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/758195/asylum2-sep-2018-tables.ods</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-12-17T17:04:23.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023213/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023213/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-12-11","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum seekers are currently living in the UK.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","201230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023214","Treasury","false","2018-12-17","<p>The off-payroll working reform in the private sector, announced at Budget 2018, is projected to increase tax receipts by nearly £3 billion over the period 2018-19 to 2023-24. This estimate has been independently assured by the Office for Budget Responsibility.</p><p> </p><p>The off-payroll working rules (commonly known as IR35) are in place to ensure that individuals who work through their own limited company (e.g. personal service company) and would have been an employee had they provided their services directly, pay broadly the same tax and National Insurance as other employees.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-12-17T16:23:49.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023214/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023214/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-12-11","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what projections his Department has produced of the tax receipts arising from the changes to IR35 rules as announced in Budget 2018.","false","Biography information for Alison McGovern","Wirral South","Alison McGovern","201166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023215","Home Office","false","2018-12-17","<p>As with all labour providers in the agricultural sector, the scheme operators for the Seasonal Workers Pilot will be required to be fully licensed by the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority. No bespoke licencing arrangements are required. <br>Full details of how the seasonal workers pilot will operate will be announced in due course. Ensuring the protection and wellbeing of participating migrant workers is of primary importance .</p><p>We are working with the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority to ensure that we get this right.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","201233","2018-12-17T16:52:05.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023215/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023215/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-12-11","Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment he has made of the level of resources required by the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority as a result of the introduction of the new seasonal workers pilot in the agricultural sector.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","201231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023216","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-12-17","<p>The paper entitled Seasonal workers pilot: request for information (RFI), published in September 2018, laid out the details of the Pilot explained Defra’s expectations of any potential Pilot Operators, and requested information from any organisation seeking to operate the Pilot to enable Defra to assess their suitability. The responses to the RFI were evaluated as part of the Pilot’s competitive selection process and two Pilot Operators were selected. The statement of changes to the Immigration rules laid out on 11 December 2018 names of the selected Pilot Operators.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-12-17T11:00:55.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023216/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023216/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-12-11","Agriculture: Seasonal Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when he plans to respond to his Department's paper entitled, Seasonal workers pilot: request for information, published in September 2018.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","201232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023217","Home Office","false","2018-12-17","<p>As with all labour providers in the agricultural sector, the scheme operators for the Seasonal Workers Pilot will be required to be fully licensed by the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority. No bespoke licencing arrangements are required. <br>Full details of how the seasonal workers pilot will operate will be announced in due course. Ensuring the protection and wellbeing of participating migrant workers is of primary importance .</p><p>We are working with the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority to ensure that we get this right.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","201231","2018-12-17T16:52:05.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023217/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023217/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-12-11","Agriculture: Seasonal Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to section 5 of the Gangmasters (Licensing) Act 2004, how the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority plans to license non-EU labour providers engaged in the seasonal workers pilot in the agricultural sector.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","201233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023218","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-12-17","<p>Defra officials are working closely with the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority (GLAA) on the Government’s seasonal workers pilot. The oversight and protection of workers was a central element of the selection process for Pilot Operators. The selected Pilot Operators were first publically announced in the Statement of changes to the Immigration Rules, which was laid on 11 December and is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/statement-of-changes-to-the-immigration-rules-hc-1779-11-december-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/statement-of-changes-to-the-immigration-rules-hc-1779-11-december-2018</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Officials will continue working closely with the GLAA over the two year operation of the Pilot. A key objective of the pilot is to ensure that migrant workers are adequately protected against modern slavery and other labour abuses. The operators of the scheme will be licensed by the GLAA. They will ensure that all workers are placed with farms who adhere to all relevant legislation, including paying the National Minimum Wage. Farmers will also be vetted to ensure that living and working conditions are of a suitable quality.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-12-17T10:51:04.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023218/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023218/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-12-11","Agriculture: Seasonal Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions his Department has had with representatives from the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority on the seasonal workers pilot.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","201234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023219","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-12-17","<p>Defra officials are working closely with the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority (GLAA) on the Government’s seasonal workers pilot. The oversight and protection of workers was a central element of the selection process for Pilot Operators. The selected Pilot Operators were first publically announced in the Statement of changes to the Immigration Rules, which was laid on 11 December and is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/statement-of-changes-to-the-immigration-rules-hc-1779-11-december-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/statement-of-changes-to-the-immigration-rules-hc-1779-11-december-2018</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Officials will continue working closely with the GLAA over the two year operation of the Pilot. A key objective of the pilot is to ensure that migrant workers are adequately protected against modern slavery and other labour abuses. The operators of the scheme will be licensed by the GLAA. They will ensure that all workers are placed with farms who adhere to all relevant legislation, including paying the National Minimum Wage. Farmers will also be vetted to ensure that living and working conditions are of a suitable quality.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-12-17T11:06:31.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023219/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023219/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-12-11","Agriculture: Seasonal Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the Seasonal Workers Pilot in the agricultural sector, how much time will be provided to the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority to develop a system for worker oversight and protection in the UK and overseas from the point at which Pilot Operators are chosen to the point at which the pilot starts to provide workers to growers and employers in the UK.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","201235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023220","Department for Transport","false","2018-12-17","<p>The award for the next franchise will now be made in the new year. We are working to deliver the best possible outcome for passengers and taxpayers and are focused on delivering a successful outcome for the competition as soon as possible.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2018-12-17T15:20:02.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023220/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023220/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-12-11","South Eastern Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 11 December to Question 198250 on the South Eastern Rail Franchise, on what date in the New Year he plans to make the announcement on the successful bidder of the new South Eastern rail franchise by; and what steps he is taking to ensure that there will not be a delay in  the new operator taking over in April 2019.","false","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","Bexleyheath and Crayford","Sir David Evennett","201123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023221","Department for Education","false","2018-12-17","<p>The Department’s guidance documents, under the Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005, highlight schools’ responsibilities to carry out risk assessments for their Fire Safety Management Plans.</p><p>The Department also specifies the fire safety requirements for notice boards in the ‘Output Specification’ documents that set out the design and construction requirements for all Department for Education delivered school buildings. In order to fully address the issue, the Department needs to carry out background research. Should the research show there is further guidance to give, the Department would then update the Output Specification and consider releasing a technical note to responsible bodies on the specification and installation of noticeboards.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-12-17T17:53:54.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023221/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023221/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-11","Schools: Notice Boards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will make and assessment of adequacy of the guidance issued to schools, local education authorities and other responsible bodies to ensure that classroom notice boards are installed correctly and in accordance with fire standards that are legally compliant.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","201108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023222","Department for Education","false","2018-12-18","<p>This is a matter for Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Amanda Spielman. I have asked her to write to the hon. Member and a copy of her reply will be placed in the Libraries of both Houses.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-12-18T11:06:56.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023222/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023222/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-11","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans (a) Ofsted and (b) the Care Quality Commission have to automatically require a written statement of action where joint commissioning arrangements for speech, language and communication needs and related needs, including (i) social, (ii) emotional and (iii) mental health, classified as inadequate.","false","Biography information for Geraint Davies","Swansea West","Geraint Davies","201090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023223","Department for Education","false","2018-12-19","<p>There are a range of existing published sources that seek to quantify the cost of exclusion, but the Department has not conducted its own assessment of the cost to the public purse of excluding a child from school.</p><p> </p><p>In March, the Government launched an externally led review of exclusions practice, led by Edward Timpson CBE. The review will consider how schools use exclusion and how this impacts on all pupils. The Government will respond to this review when it is published at the beginning of next year.</p><p>The full terms of reference for the review can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-exclusions-review-terms-of-reference" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-exclusions-review-terms-of-reference</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-12-19T17:20:21.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023223/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023223/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-11","Pupil Exclusions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of excluding a child from school.","false","Biography information for Geraint Davies","Swansea West","Geraint Davies","201091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023224","Cabinet Office","false","2019-01-14","<p>I responded to Question 189621 on 09/01/19. The response can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-11-09/189621/" target="_blank">https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-11-09/189621/</a></p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2019-01-14T17:31:29.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023224/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023224/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-12-11","Cabinet Office: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when he plans to answer Question 189621 on the membership of the Financial, Professional and Education Services Business Council tabled on 9 November 2018 by the hon. Member for Bristol East.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","201124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023225","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>We are very concerned about the reports that these executions may be imminent and we are closely monitoring these cases. We last raised these concerns on 20 November and 3 December, when we discussed both the substance of the cases and the UK’s long standing opposition to the death penalty. It is a longstanding policy of the British Government to oppose the death penalty, in all circumstances, as a matter of principle.</p><p>We consistently and unreservedly condemn torture and cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment and it is a priority for us to combat it wherever and whenever it occurs.</p><p>We have been and do continually raise our concerns including on this case with the Saudi Arabian authorities using a range of Ministerial and diplomatic channels of communication, including our Ambassador.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","201167","2018-12-19T15:23:02.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023225/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023225/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Saudi Arabia: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Saudi Arabian counterpart on the planned execution of Abbas al-Hassan and 11 other individuals for exercising their rights to freedom of religion and association.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023226","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>We are very concerned about the reports that these executions may be imminent and we are closely monitoring these cases. We last raised these concerns on 20 November and 3 December, when we discussed both the substance of the cases and the UK’s long standing opposition to the death penalty. It is a longstanding policy of the British Government to oppose the death penalty, in all circumstances, as a matter of principle.</p><p>We consistently and unreservedly condemn torture and cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment and it is a priority for us to combat it wherever and whenever it occurs.</p><p>We have been and do continually raise our concerns including on this case with the Saudi Arabian authorities using a range of Ministerial and diplomatic channels of communication, including our Ambassador.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","201125","2018-12-19T15:23:02.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023226/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023226/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Saudi Arabia: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the Government of Saudi Arabia's compliance with international agreements on the use of torture, forced confessions and capital punishment in the sentencing of Abbas al-Hassan and eleven other individuals for exercising their rights to freedom of religion and association.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023227","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>We remain deeply concerned about Israa al Ghomgham and continue to closely monitor developments. It is a longstanding policy of the British Government to oppose the death penalty, in all circumstances, as a matter of principle.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-12-19T15:24:53.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023227/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023227/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Israa al-Ghomgham ","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Saudi Arabian counterpart on the planned execution of Israa al-Ghomgham for demanding greater rights for women in that country.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023228","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>The UK is closely following the issues of the sentences imposed on human rights defenders in Saudi Arabia and the use of the Special Criminal Court (SCC) to prosecute activists. Our Ambassador in Riyadh regularly raises this issue with the Saudi Authorities. Representatives of our Embassy in Riyadh attend all trials of activists at the SCC that they are permitted to by the authorities. We raise our concerns at all levels and at all appropriate opportunities, including through our Ambassador, Embassy staff and through the EU.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-12-19T15:25:52.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023228/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023228/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Saudi Arabia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his counterpart in Saudi Arabia on the use of that country’s Specialised Criminal Court to prosecute and convict individuals seeking to protest or exercise their human rights in that country.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023229","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>The British government continues to follow the trial of Professor Chan Kin-Man and other leaders of the ‘Occupy’ Movement in Hong Kong.</p><p>Individual cases regarding pro-democracy activists are a matter for the Hong Kong courts. The British Government hopes that these and other recent criminal proceedings do not discourage lawful protest, nor discourage young people from engaging in politics in the future. I visited Hong Kong in November and made clear the UK’s continued commitment to the Joint Declaration, and to the faithful implementation of the ‘One Country, Two Systems’ agreement, which guarantees rights and freedoms to Hong Kong’s people.</p><p>​</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-12-19T16:42:12.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023229/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023229/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Chan Kin-man","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Chinese counterpart on the prosecution of Professor Chan Kin-Man; and what assessment he has made on whether the potential imprisonment of Professor Chan Kin-Ma complies with the 1984 Sino-British Joint Declaration.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023230","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>We note with concern by the decision of the Hong Kong SAR Government to prohibit the Hong Kong National Party. This is the first time a party has been banned under the Societies Ordinance since the handover of Hong Kong to China in 1997.</p><p>Under the doctrine of 'One Country, Two Systems' the UK does not support Hong Kong independence, but Hong Kong’s high degree of autonomy and its rights and freedoms are central to its way of life, and it is important they are fully respected.</p><p>I visited Hong Kong in November and made clear that recent events, including the banning of the Hong Kong National Party, are putting Hong Kong’s rights and freedoms under increasing pressure. He noted the UK’s continued commitment to the Joint Declaration, and to the faithful implementation of the ‘One Country, Two Systems’ agreement, which guarantees rights and freedoms for Hong Kong’s people.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-12-19T16:45:55.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023230/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023230/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Chinese counterpart on the banning of the Hong Kong National Party; and what assessment he has made on whether the decision to ban that party complies with the 1984 Sino-British Joint Declaration.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023231","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>The Foreign Secretary last spoke with his Brazilian counterpart on 14 September to discuss a range of bilateral issues. We are working with Brazil to help ensure it continues to protect the Amazon and those who live within it.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-12-19T13:25:35.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023231/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023231/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Amazonia: Forests and Indigenous Peoples","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Brazilian counterpart on the protection of the Amazon rainforest and its indigenous tribes.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023232","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>I was pleased to hear that President-elect Bolsonaro confirmed on 25 October that Brazil will not be withdrawing from the Paris Climate Change Agreement.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-12-19T13:26:42.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023232/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023232/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Brazil: Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Brazilian counterpart on that country’s commitment to the Paris Climate Change Agreement.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023233","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>There are no plans for a State Visit by President-elect Bolsonaro.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-12-19T13:29:57.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023233/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023233/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Brazil: State Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the Government's position is on providing a State Visit to President Bolsonaro of Brazil.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023234","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>We have raised concerns following reports of civilian casualties and displacement resulting from recent Taliban attacks in districts predominantly populated by Hazaras. We continue to monitor the situation closely, especially in Ghazni and Uruzgan districts. We understand that the Afghan National Defence and Security Forces (ANDSF) are working to stabilise the security situation in both provinces.</p><p>We urge the Government of Afghanistan to protect the rights of all ethnic and religious groups, including the Hazaras, in line with the Afghan constitution. The UK provides a range of support which aims to enhance the Afghan Government’s ability to protect all Afghan citizens. Through DFID, we have contributed £42 million towards lifesaving humanitarian aid in Afghanistan this year. The UK is also committed to supporting the Afghan Security Forces to ensure their capability continues to improve in order to protect all ethnic and religious groups in Afghanistan. We contribute to this through the UK’s contribution to NATO’s Resolute Support Mission.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-12-19T16:49:12.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023234/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023234/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Afghanistan: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to help the Afghan authorities respond effectively to attacks on the Hazara community in Afghanistan and to prevent the occurrence of future attacks.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023235","Department for International Development","false","2018-12-19","<p>The UK is extremely concerned about the humanitarian situation in Afghanistan and as a result of UK funding, up to two million Afghans will receive lifesaving assistance in 2018. Provision of humanitarian assistance is based on need. It includes shelter and heating support to help displaced people face the winter, as well as food assistance for those affected by drought, lifesaving health &amp; nutrition services, clean water, and demining activities. As recently announced at the Geneva Conference on Afghanistan, we have increased our funding for the humanitarian response to £67 million this year. We continue to press others to do more.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-12-19T16:02:57.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023235/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023235/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-12-11","Afghanistan: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what additional humanitarian aid the Government is giving in advance of the upcoming winter months to help Hazara families displaced by recent violence against their communities in Afghanistan.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023236","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>I have not spoken to the US deputy Secretary of State about this particular policy. The UK has been working with the UN to agree a Global Compact which offers refugees a viable future and is set for adoption by the end of the year. We have actively participated in its development from the beginning and have engaged with other Member States and interested parties, including the United States. The UK is at the forefront of responding to forced displacement and refugee crises around the world and we are one of the most significant contributors to UNHCR, including £100m last year, along with a commitment to provide £35m annually in core funding through to 2021.</p><p>​</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-12-19T13:31:30.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023236/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023236/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","USA: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his US counterpart on the planned reduction in the number of refugees to be admitted to that country next year to 30,000 from the 90,000 admitted each year under the previous administration; and what plans he has to lead international efforts to fill the gap created by that reduction.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023237","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>The British government welcomes the decision of the Pakistan government to grant registered Afghans the right to remain in Pakistan until June 2019. We also welcome last month’s second meeting of the Refugee Working Group between the Pakistani and Afghan governments. The British government continues to advocate for the rights of Afghan refugees, and follows developments closely.</p><p>​</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-12-19T16:51:03.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023237/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023237/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Pakistan: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Pakistani counterpart on the citizenship status of the 1.5 million children of Afghan refugees currently living in that country.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023238","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>The UK Government’s primary concern is for the safety and well-being of Asia Bibi and her family. We want to see a swift, positive resolution to the case.</p><p>It is the long standing position of the Government not to comment on individual immigration issues.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-12-19T16:53:12.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023238/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023238/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Asia Bibi ","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether his Department instructed the Home Office not to offer asylum to Asia Bibi due to concerns for the safety of British consular staff in Pakistan.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023239","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>We have not made any representations on this specific case, however, the UK is committed to holding Iran to account on a wide range of human rights issues, through contact with the Iranian government and internationally through the EU and UN. We have also designated Iran as one of our Human Rights Priority Countries.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-12-19T15:27:35.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023239/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023239/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Golrokh Ebrahimi Iraee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Iranian counterpart on the detention of Golrokh Ebrahimi Iraee for insulting Islamic sanctities by advocating against the use of stoning as a punishment.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023240","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>We are particularly concerned by the continuing systematic discrimination, harassment and targeting of the Baha’i community. The British government supports the UN Special Rapporteur’s assessment that discrimination against the Baha’i community in Iran is legally sanctioned by a lack of constitutional recognition and the absence of other legal protections for adherents of this faith. Though we have not raised specifically the cases of Farajollah Bangaleh and Mitra Badrnejad, we have repeatedly expressed concern at the ongoing incarceration, and the shocking sentencing of Baha'i leaders and the wider community in Iran with the Iranian authorities.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-12-19T15:28:44.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023240/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023240/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Iran: Baha'i Faith","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Iranian counterpart on the jailing of (a) Farajollah Bangaleh and (b) Mitra Badrnejad for practicing their Ba’hai faith; and whether he raised the Iranian authority's treatment of the Ba’hai people on his recent trip to Tehran.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023241","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-12-19","<p>The UK is fully committed to the promotion of media freedom and the protection of journalists. The Foreign Secretary has announced our intention to launch in 2019 an international campaign to end the climate of impunity and mobilise a consensus behind the protection of journalists worldwide. We are currently considering how this campaign can best add value and reinforce existing mechanisms, including those of the UN and other international organisations. We have held discussions with Reporters Without Borders and are actively reviewing their proposal for a dedicated UN postion on this issue. ​</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-12-19T16:55:36.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023241/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023241/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-11","Journalism and Press Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of calls from Reporters Without Borders for the creation of a UN Special Rapporteur with responsibility for monitoring the protection of journalists and press freedom.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","201182"
