"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023004","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-12-13","<p>We have a long history of collaborating with European partners through multilateral and bilateral initiatives across education, civil society, sport and our creative and cultural industries. We want a positive future relationship that reflects our shared values and history, and will support the growth of culture, arts, sports and creative industries, in both the UK and the EU. This government recognises the importance of mobility and the Political Declaration contains a specific reference to the importance of mobility in enabling cooperation in the cultural and education sectors.</p><p> </p><p>In the unlikely event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal, we welcome the EU Commission’s proposal to grant UK citizens visa-free travel (for short stays of up to 90 days in any 180-day period) to the EU after the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union.</p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2018-12-13T13:01:04.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023004/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023004/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023004/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-12-10","Writers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the ability of UK writers to travel to the EU for (a) writing trips, (b) residencies and (c) poetry performances after the UK has left the EU; and what assessment he has made of the ability of UK writers to undertake such activities in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","200592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023005","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-12-13","<p>The Department has no current plans to amend the list of medical conditions that provide exemption from prescription charges, as extensive arrangements are in place to ensure that people can access affordable prescriptions. The Government is considering the recommendations from the ‘Modernising the Mental Health Act: Increasing choice, reducing compulsion’ report, published on 6 December 2018.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-12-13T16:25:12.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023005/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023005/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023005/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-10","Prescriptions: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if his Department will undertake a review of the categories of conditions eligible for medical exemption certificates for NHS prescriptions to ensure that there is provision for mental health conditions.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","200637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023006","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-12-13","<p>A number of EU Member States operate their own public lending rights schemes which enable payments to be made to eligible rights holders for the lending of their work. However, these are not directly reciprocal to the UK’s Public Lending Right (PLR) Scheme, and decisions on whether UK-resident authors qualify for these will be for each Member State to make.</p><p> </p><p>The Authors' Licensing and Collecting Society (ALCS), which represents UK authors in registering and claiming payments from lending rights schemes in Europe and elsewhere, has indicated that it supports the UK's PLR scheme remaining open to residents of EEA states. ALCS believes that this will help it to encourage relevant organisations responsible for lending rights schemes in EEA states to allow UK-resident authors to benefit from such schemes after the UK leaves the EU.</p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2018-12-13T13:02:15.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023006/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023006/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023006/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-12-10","Writers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the reciprocal relationships the UK has with the EU that enable UK authors to claim public lending right payments when their books are borrowed in other EU countries.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","200593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023007","Home Office","false","2018-12-18","<p>The most recent published data on citizenship applications (November 2018) shows that 99.6% of applications were determined within the service standard of six months. Naturalisation is not an automatic process and the Home Office has to conduct a number of checks before it can reach a decision on whether to grant citizenship.</p><p>The extent and length of time taken to complete the checks on the more complex cases varies according to the particular circumstance of each case. The progress of these checks is closely monitored and decisions are made when the checks are completed.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-12-18T14:34:10.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023007/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023007/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023007/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-12-10","British Nationality: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps he is taking to tackle the issue of citizenship applications taking longer to process than the service standard of six months.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Chuka Umunna","200713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023008","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-12-18","<p>The following table shows the expenditure on children and young people’s mental health services from 2013/14 to 2017/18. Information on expenditure for 2012-13 and earlier is not available.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2017/18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Clinical commissioning group spend</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>£516 million</p></td><td><p>£619 million</p></td><td><p>£687 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Specialised commissioning spend</p></td><td><p>£252 million</p></td><td><p>£260 million</p></td><td><p>£319 million</p></td><td><p>£342 million</p></td><td><p>£361 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>£836 million</p></td><td><p>£961 million</p></td><td><p>£1,048 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: NHS England</p><p> </p><p>The 2019 Budget confirmed that the National Health Service will continue to increase mental health investment, by at least £2 billion a year in real terms by 2023/24.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-12-18T17:37:16.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023008/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023008/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023008/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-10","Mental Health Services: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much funding was allocated from the public purse to mental health services for young people in each year from 2010 to 2018.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Chuka Umunna","200714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023009","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-12-13","<p>The Department is unable to confirm the number of staff that have left permanently and subsequently joined the Building Research Establishment, as this information is not held. <br> <br> We can confirm that the Department has not seconded any staff from this organisation to work for the Building Research Establishment during the last five years.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-12-13T16:46:34.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023009/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023009/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023009/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-12-10","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many staff of his Department have (a) left his Department and (b) been seconded from his Department to work for the Building Research Establishment in each of the last five years .","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","200715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023010","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-12-18","<p>This information is not held in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement estimate as at 30 September 2018, around 80% of nursing vacancies and 85% of medical vacancies are being filled by a combination of bank and agency staff.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2018-12-18T14:04:31.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023010/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023010/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023010/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-10","NHS: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to NHS Improvement's Quarter three 2017-18 performance report, published in February 2018, how many of the (a) 35,000 nurse vacancies and (b) nearly 10,000 doctor post vacancies identified in that report have now been filled.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Chuka Umunna","200716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023011","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-12-13","<p>We are unable to confirm the number of staff, if any, currently working for the Department who have a previous period of employment with the Building Research Establishment, as this information is not held.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-12-13T16:47:59.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023011/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023011/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023011/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-12-10","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many staff of his Department have previously been employed by the Building Research Establishment.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","200717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023012","Cabinet Office","false","2018-12-18","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-12-18T14:27:19.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023012/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023012/answer","PQ 200718 Holding (1).pdf","PQ 200718 Holding (1).pdf","UKSA Response","UKSA Response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023012/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-12-10","Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the number of unreported crimes in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Chuka Umunna","200718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023013","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-12-18","<p>The information requested is not centrally collated and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>We are spending over £3 billion over 10 years on Transitional Protections for 1.1 million households, to ensure that people don’t lose out at the point of transition.</p><p> </p><p>Once managed migration has been completed there will be an additional £2.1 billion spend per year on Universal Credit compared to the current legacy system it replaces.</p><p> </p><p>Simplification of welfare through Universal Credit will lead to increased take-up of entitlement as only one application is required where previously there may have been several. This will be worth £2.4 billion per year for claimants when Universal Credit is fully rolled out, as set out in the Universal Credit Full Business Case Summary. Universal Credit also provides more help with childcare costs, scraps the 16-hour ‘cliff edge’ and the prohibitive tax rates should someone start work.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-12-18T18:14:58.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023013/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023013/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023013/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-12-10","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of people that were in receipt legacy payments are financially better off as a result of the move to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Chuka Umunna","200719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023014","Treasury","false","2018-12-13","<p>I refer the Rt Hon Gentleman to my answer to him on 29 November in response to <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-11-26/195459/" target="_blank">written question 195459</a>. Further detail building on the agreement in the political declaration will be set out by the UK and EU as part of negotiations on the future relationship.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-12-13T14:25:16.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023014/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023014/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023014/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-12-10","Financial Services: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the oral contribution of 6 December 2018, Official Report, column 1091, if he will publish the enhanced equivalence arrangements for regulating financial services between the UK and the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","200541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023015","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-12-17","<p>In 2018/19, NHS Business Services Authority has been awarded an annual budget allocation of up to £46.3 million from the Department to provide support for those affected by infected blood.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-12-17T14:53:32.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023015/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023015/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023015/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-10","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what resources have been allocated to the NHS Business Services Authority to support victims of the contaminated blood scandal.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","200720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023016","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-12-13","<p>Public Health England (PHE) and Drinkaware’s ‘Drink Free days’ campaign, launched in September 2018, highlighted the links between alcohol and cancer.</p><p> </p><p>The campaign website includes information about alcohol increasing the risk of at least seven types of cancer, with a particular focus on bowel cancer, breast cancer and oral cancer. The Drink Free Days campaign website is available to view at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.drinkaware.co.uk/drink-free-days/" target="_blank">https://www.drinkaware.co.uk/drink-free-days/</a></p><p> </p><p>The links between alcohol and cancer are also highlighted in PHE’s One You campaign, available to view at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/oneyou/for-your-body/drink-less/" target="_blank">https://www.nhs.uk/oneyou/for-your-body/drink-less/</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-12-13T16:23:33.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023016/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023016/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023016/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-10","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to increase public awareness of the link between alcohol consumption and cancer.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","200638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023017","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-12-13","<p>We work closely with the telecoms sector on matters of resilience and security through the industry led Electronic Communications Resilience and Response Group. Furthermore, the Communication Act 2003 (section 105A) requires telecoms operators to have appropriate measures in place to manage risks to the security (covering confidentiality, integrity and availability) of networks and services. Telecoms operators are also required to notify Ofcom of security and resilience issues (including service outages) which have a ‘significant impact on the operation of a network or service’ (section 105B Communications Act 2003).</p><p> </p><p>Ofcom reports annually on the number and scale of security incidents, including impacts (ie numbers of customers affected) through their Connected Nations report.</p><p> </p><p>Compensation arrangements linked to a service incident are a matter for the company but Ofcom will be discussing the company’s plans with them.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","200595 ; 200596 ; 200597","2018-12-13T17:52:14.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023017/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023017/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1023017/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-12-10","O2","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the effect on the UK economy of the O2 data failure of 6 December 2018.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","200594"
